properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for today. Snow, at times heavy, will accumulate to 5 to 10 centimetres by early this afternoon, then switch over to showers mixed at times with wet flurries this afternoon. Poor winter driving conditions from low visibility in occasional heavy snow and local blowing snow are expected into this afternoon. Motorists should allow extra time to reach their destination. This winter weather travel advisory replaces the snowfall warning which was previously in effect, as total snowfall amounts are no longer expected to reach the warning threshold of 15 cm in a 12 hour period. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: High Water Level Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. Locations: north facing shorelines from Notre Dame Bay to Ferryland. Maximum water levels: significantly exceeding high astronomical tide. Maximum wave heights: 9 to 12 metres, breaking upon approach to shore. Time span: continuing until early this afternoon, peaking during high tide. Remarks: Higher than normal water levels along the east and northeast coasts due to 60 to 80 cm of storm surge combined with 9 to 12 m waves are expected to persist until early this afternoon. Flooding and damage to coastal infrastructure is possible, especially in locations exposed to the north. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain near Hope beginning late afternoon. A strong storm system will bring snow to the Fraser Valley. Warm air aloft pushes inland this afternoon and freezing rain is expected for portions of the Coquihalla and the Hope Princeton Highways, near Hope. Higher elevations of these routes will likely see a transition to rain showers by this evening. Freezing rain could persist into Sunday. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots will become icy, slippery and hazardous. Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. The storm system affecting southern Manitoba continues to bring snow, gusty northwest winds and blowing snow to region. Snowfall totals across the regions are highly variable. However, radar and surface reports indicate the highest amounts thus far have fallen west of the City of Winnipeg along a line north to south in the vicinity of Portage la Prairie stretching northward into the Interlake and southward towards the US border. The following amounts are snowfall totals from Friday morning to early this morning. These reports are from the CoCoRaHS network and are in centimetres. Winnipeg 5.1 to 10.9 Portage la Prairie 12.2 Steinbach 7.6 Woodlands 15.2 St. Francois Xavier 19.6 Pinawa 15.5 Morris 8.9 High Bluff 8.1 Zhoda 6.4 St. Pierre Jolys 7.1 Snow and blowing snow will continue today with storm total snowfall accumulations of 10 to 25 cm by the time the it tapers off this evening. Northwest winds will continue to strengthen today with gusts up to 70 km/h. These winds combined with the falling snow will cause significantly reduced visibilities in blowing snow. Conditions will gradually improve Saturday evening. Anyone who needs to travel on area highways today should ensure that they check local weather forecasts (https://weather.gc.ca/forecast/canada/index_e.html?id=mb) and regional highway conditions (https://manitoba511.ca/en/) before travelling. Ensure that your vehicle contains a winter emergency kit (https://www.getprepared.gc.ca/cnt/rsrcs/sfttps/tp201012-en.aspx) in case poor travelling conditions cause you to be stranded for a period of time. Travel conditions have also deteriorated through the Dakotas and Minnesota, where this disturbance has also brought snow and strong winds. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

Description: Hazardous winter conditions are expected. The winter storm is almost over. Heavy wet snow occurring over a few inland locations will switch to rain early this morning. There is also the risk of freezing rain for Inland Vancouver Island. ### Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-18T19:34:00-00:00

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall and blowing snow today. Snow, heavy at times, will continue into this afternoon. Total snowfall accumulations of 15 to 25 cm are expected by the time the snow tapers to flurries early Sunday morning. Easterly winds gusting up to 60 km/h will cause widespread blowing snow today making travel difficult across the area. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
Expires: 2020-01-19T08:03:25-00:00
